The part that's dealing with the development and advancement program for the college is exciting and challenging and most ambiguous.
Because there's no part of it structured at this point.
The amorphous problem of trying to sort out what the priorities of the college are, who might be interested in which priorities, who might deal with what will be resolved.

And you worked with the Development Council, or you were part of it since the very beginning.
Can you give me just a couple of sentences on how you feel that that has evolved, or did evolve, or where it could go?
Collison College has never clearly specified what it wants from the Development Council.
It's been very satisfied at times with what it got, and very dissatisfied at times with what it got, and nobody knows why.
Until the
The college gives the Development Council a clear statement of priority.
It's unlikely that we can get it.
The thing that is being confused at the Development Council is advice and advancement.
If you want a group for advice, you give them the problems you're seeking advice about.
If you want a group for advancement, you outline the program that you have in mind and seek their assistance.
And we've confused the two.
That's what I think I've learned so far.
OK.
In closing, you have any words of wisdom or anything that you want to bring closer?
Well, I'm sure you're going to find lots and lots and lots of variation in perception.
Oh, absolutely.
The College of Ed, in my opinion, has made enormous strides in the 12 years that I've been here.
It has not, however, decided whether it wants to be a top-flight research college or whether it wants to do teacher education.
and in what mix it wants to do them.
